.TH XXD(1),User Commands,XXD(1)

.SH NAME
xxd - hex dump of a file

.SH SYNOPSIS
xxd [-h] [-c cols] [-w width] [file ...]

.SH DESCRIPTION
xxd prints each named file as a hex dump.
Each output line has an offset, a group of hex-encoded bytes, and a text rendering in which non-printable bytes are shown as a dot.

With no file operand, xxd reads from standard input.

When multiple files are given, their dumps are concatenated with no separator;
the offset is shared across files and continues to grow.

.SH OPTIONS
-c cols: Number of bytes per row.
Default is 16.
cols is parsed as decimal, or hex with a leading $ or 0x.

-w width: Width of the printed offset, in hex digits, 1 through 4.
Default is 4.
Values outside 1..4 are silently ignored.

-h: Print a short usage summary and exit 0.

.SH DIAGNOSTICS
xxd: unknown option -- X - an unrecognised flag was given.

xxd: option requires an argument -- X - -c or -w was given with no argument.

xxd: FILE: No such file exists - a named file could not be opened.

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: All files dumped.

1: A file could not be opened, or an invalid option was supplied.

.SH SEE ALSO
strings(1)
